{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17529902","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17529902"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:00:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:00:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14474"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14474","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14474"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.07,0.71,0.18,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7169"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55689"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7169","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7169"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14474"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41232"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1374"},{"type":"tags","id":"2451"},{"type":"tags","id":"4423"},{"type":"tags","id":"4425"},{"type":"tags","id":"4432"},{"type":"tags","id":"4483"},{"type":"tags","id":"12800"},{"type":"tags","id":"12805"},{"type":"tags","id":"12915"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17204"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26881"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55689","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55689"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the labour ward at 40 weeks gestation. She reports reduced fetal movements over the past 24 hours. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 125/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. The cervix is 4 cm dilated. Artificial rupture of membranes reveals thick meconium-stained liquor. Cardiotocography (CTG) is commenced.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe CTG trace shows a baseline fetal heart rate of 145 beats/min with reduced variability. There are repetitive decelerations that start mid each contraction and continue for 30 seconds after each contraction has ceased. The fetal heart rate drops to 100 beats/min with each deceleration with slow recovery. The decelerations occur with every contraction.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Administer terbutaline","Continue to monitor CTG","Prepare for immediate caesarean section","Perform fetal blood sampling","Administer intravenous fluids"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis scenario presents a woman in labour with several concerning features: reduced fetal movements, meconium-stained liquor, and an abnormal CTG showing late decelerations. These findings suggest fetal distress and require prompt action.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPreparing for immediate caesarean section\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step. Late decelerations on CTG are a sign of uteroplacental insufficiency and fetal hypoxia. When persistent and combined with other risk factors like meconium-stained liquor and reduced fetal movements, they indicate a need for urgent delivery to prevent further fetal compromise.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinuing to monitor CTG\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate in this situation. The CTG already shows clear signs of fetal distress, and further monitoring without intervention could lead to worsening fetal condition and potential adverse outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdministering terbutaline\u003C/strong\u003E, a tocolytic, could be considered if the CTG was less concerning than in this scenario. Tocolytics can be used to suppress contractions especially in the context of fetal bradycardia due to high uterine tone. In this case of term labour with fetal distress, tocolysis would delay necessary delivery and potentially worsen fetal hypoxia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerforming fetal blood sampling\u003C/strong\u003E (FBS) can be considered in some cases of suspicious CTG to assess fetal acid-base status. However, in this case, with clear signs of fetal compromise (late decelerations, reduced variability, meconium, and reduced movements), FBS would unnecessarily delay delivery without changing management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdministering intravenous fluids\u003C/strong\u003E is a supportive measure that can be used in labour, but it would not address the immediate concern of fetal distress in this scenario. While hydration is important, it would not be the most appropriate next step given the urgency of the situation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, the combination of reduced fetal movements, meconium-stained liquor, and a CTG showing late decelerations indicates significant fetal compromise. Immediate delivery via caesarean section is the safest course of action to prevent further fetal hypoxia and potential adverse outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Late decelerations on CTG are indicative of uteroplacental insufficiency and fetal hypoxia.","The presence of meconium in the amniotic fluid, especially with an abnormal CTG, increases the risk of adverse fetal outcomes.","Prompt delivery is indicated when there are persistent late decelerations and other signs of fetal distress."],"references":["Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists. Intrapartum fetal surveillance clinical guideline \u2013 Fourth edition. East Melbourne: RANZCOG; 2019. Available from: https://ranzcog.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Intrapartum-Fetal-Surveillance.pdf","National Institute for Health and Care Excellence. Intrapartum care for healthy women and babies. London: NICE; 2017. (NICE guideline [CG190])."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41232"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14474"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41232","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41232"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-17T14:45:15+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-17T14:46:09+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7169"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55689"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.eme